Owner & Employee
Owner is defined as an individual which bootstraps a company with a minimum of 40% of personal-assets and works full-time on the endeavor.
No Partnerships nor conglomeration are allowed to own a company. 

One company maximum per owner.
One business-parcel of land per company.

One process of transfer of ownership: inheritance by heir.
Companies are tied to the family lineage.
A company is dissolved by the sale of assets.

Owners have executive power & gains.
Employees have stability & gains.
Convergence is to longevity by a healthy strong foundation.
Society & business rely upon each other symbiotically.

Exist three types of stocks which reflect the three types of individuals associated with a business.

Owner Stock
Gains of initial investment will not exceed 400% of original bootstrap investment.
These gains are paid back at an annual rate lower than 20% annual.
Owner-stock is bound by inheritance any the gains on initial investment carry-forward.
Owner has the singular executive role within the company.
The role of owner is reflective of the role of the King.

Employee Stock
Employees receive a ratio of all gains tied to their contribution.
Employees have voting rights upon major company decisions.
Employee veto forces a compromise which favors the owner by 3:2 proportion.
Employee’s contributions are calculated based upon daily open-source metrics.
Keystone position of contribution-metrics instill focus of the individual from child to adult.
Integrity of the system in based upon nature of man to check correct calculation of self & others.
Explicit contribution-metrics are compiled over the lifetime of that engagement.
	{ time, overtime, holiday, stress, commitment, implementations }
AI & Auditor, chosen by employee, will oversee probationary periods required before termination of employee from company.
Employee stock is bound to the profits & gains produced from interval of involvement scaled by the ratio of contribution-metrics. This is carry-forward to heir.

Investor Stock
Idle investors gains common stock which is capped at a return of 10% annual.
Investor gains are only received after fulfillment of employee gains.
Investors are barred from interfering in company implementation.
Common stock has no voting rights.

